> RITHOLTZ：那么，我们将详细讨论长期牛市和熊市。是什么导致了导致泡沫的时代精神。我们将讨论很多非常有趣的事情。市场价格反映了什么，没有反映什么？我们等待已久的令人讨厌的衰退到底在哪里？</p><p>但现在我想坚持这样一个事实：与传统的战略家或宏观经济学家不同，你为战略和分析的世界带来了非常具体的哲学倾向，这是我非常感兴趣的。是什么促使这种方法来撰写有关经济、美联储或人工智能等枯燥技术主题的文章？</p><p>米安：我的意思是，一些最伟大的作家，巴里，拥有与他们的经历非常奇怪的才能。如果你想想赫尔曼·梅尔维尔，他就无法忍受船上的生活。他写了《白鲸》。欧内斯特·海明威虽然远离战争，但他成为了有史以来最伟大的战时作家。杰克·凯鲁亚克以游牧闻名，他在母亲家里写下了《在路上》。简·奥斯汀仍然单身，但她成为了受人尊敬的求爱、爱情和婚姻的编年史。你知道，艾米莉·勃朗特喜欢独来独往，但当她写《呼啸山庄》时，人们认为这是一个男人写的，因为她描绘了一个如此恶毒残酷的世界。艾米莉·狄金森，你知道，她喜欢独处，在她的诗歌中，她揭示了宇宙的秘密。</p><p>所以当我问自己这个问题时，我有资格提供投资建议吗？我意识到，在所有这些情况下，他们与主题的距离并没有削弱他们的可信度。这只会让他们更加好奇，并以其他人可能不会的方式进行检查。所以在很长一段时间里，我实际上认为我的非传统背景，我不是常春藤盟校的学生，我没有在投资银行接受过培训，我没有为对冲基金工作，我的职业生涯始于银行柜员。在很长一段时间里，我都认为非传统的背景是一种缺点。但多年来，在社区的帮助和鼓励下，我意识到，这实际上是一种核心优势，因为你怎么能以不同于绝大多数西方出生和训练有素的分析师的方式看待世界呢？</p><p> RITHOLTZ：你说“以不同的方式看待世界”这句话很有趣。最近《华尔街日报》的一篇文章说，90%的投行经济学家都毕业于同一六所研究生院。这意味着，尽管我们愿意认为存在一些思想差异，但本质上是同一家工厂生产相同的小部件。他们或多或少都说了同样的话，我们对此并不感到惊讶。</p><p>我们将谈论永远即将到来但似乎永远不会到来的经济衰退。但这似乎与具有相同背景的同一群人将产生相同的投资结果密切相关。这或多或少公平吗？</p><p>面：我不能和别人说话。我知道-</p><p> RITHOLTZ：嗯，你真是太慷慨了。</p><p>米安：但是，看，当我创办这家公司时，我意识到我所做的事情并不是独一无二的，因为还有很多其他人在写关于市场的观点，但我是独一无二的。 。因此，我一直坚持从个人空间进行写作，真正培养写作技巧，真正客观地审视市场，在我的分析中变得非常不可知论，而不是意识形态和经验主义，而不是教条主义。</p><p>所以我不在乎是一致的还是逆向的，看涨还是看跌。我只想独立并了解真相。</p><p>里索兹：所以在你的很多著作中，你引用了老子、佛陀、孔子、塞内卡。这是各种各样的影响。是什么让您认识了这群思想家？这些伟大的哲学家如何影响您对市场问题的思考？</p><p>面：你看，我认为生活和市场是交织在一起的。市场中最大的风险是自我。我想说生命中最大的风险是自我。市场和生活中最大的美德就是谦虚。我常说，成功的投资只有在了解自己的情况下才有可能。所以我认为对我来说，当我开始写作时，这既是一个自我探究的过程，也是一个审视市场的过程。你会看到重叠和相似之处以及不断出现的偏见和常见错误。你只需要不断培养更好的自己并不断进步。</p><p>我觉得关于古代智慧有很多话可说。好像所有的事情都已经说过了，但是没有人听，所以又被报道了，又被说了一遍。</p><p>所以我从古代圣贤、诗人、哲学家的美德、智慧中受益匪浅。我认为它可以帮助我看清世界。你知道，我相信我们的内心越清晰，我们看待事物的能力就越清晰。所以你引用的所有这些人都在帮助我成为一个更好的人，意识到我的偏见，并且只是，是的，成为一个更清晰的思考者。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：那么让我们来谈谈自我和谦逊。所有最好的投资者都认识到自己的错误，没有人能击中一千个，我们都经常犯错误。 Ray Dalio 的《原理》一书本质上是一篇关于 Go 尝试某件事、犯一个错误、从错误中吸取教训并融入到你的过程中、再试一次的论文。</p><p>但即使大声说出来，听起来仍然相当激进。为什么我们不能接受这样一个事实：投资是一门令人谦卑的艺术，需要其从业者保持谦逊？</p><p>米安：巴里，我的想法是再次从精神角度出发，所有的先知都做了这个特殊的祈祷。 “哦上帝，请让我们看到事物本来的样子。”所以对我来说，目标是看到事物本来的样子，而不是我想要的样子。所以当我使用“应该”这样的词时，我什至会注意自己。市场应该这样运作。我认为这是虚伪的。市场不应该以这样或那样的方式表现。就是这样，对吧？所以我有一个特定的观点，你有你的观点，然后有一个神圣的观点，或者市场观点。那么如何才能接近这个事实呢？只有摆脱你自己，摆脱你的自我，坚持市场以特定的方式运行。我很好奇，你知道吗？这是一个很大的区别。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我总是想到各种策略师、经济学家、交易员等等。我想说，这就像约翰·萨克斯关于六个盲人描述大象的诗。每个人都抓住了其中的一个小方面。哦，这个绳状的东西是尾巴，这是象牙。但很少有人能够凭借自己的优势看到整个市场。</p><p> MIAN：我认为这就是社区发挥作用的地方，对吗？因为我并不自称是大师或市场专家。我只是真的很好奇，我很高兴知道并承认我并不知道一切。坦率地说，这是我一生中最伟大的自由化之一，因为我不需要知道一切，我也不需要知道一切，我可以依赖和信任社区内的其他人。</p><p>所以我对某个特定主题没有特别强烈的看法。我会去看专家并与他或她交谈。这样我就可以依靠社区。再次强调，我们所有人都比任何人都聪明。我没有特定的自我需要以特定的方式呈现和表达。我很高兴地说，我不知道什么时候我真的不知道。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：嗯，真的很有趣。让我们来谈谈您去年 8 月发表的文章，当时正值股票和债券同年首次出现两位数低迷时期，在短短 40 年的时间里，您定义并讨论了长期牛市，这引起了人们的强烈共鸣我。在进一步讨论之前，我们先来定义一下，什么是长期牛市？</p><p>米安：所以，长期牛市将是一段较长时期，股票回报率高于平均水平，期间会出现回调，但回调的持续时间和幅度都比预期的要短，而且复苏很快，风险偏好也会上升。估值攀升或扩大，长期熊市将反之亦然，对吗？事实上，风险偏好正在下降，下跌时间较长、深度较大，估值意味着回归。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：让我们举几个例子。</p><p>告诉我们二战后的长期牛市。 How would you define and characterize that period?</p><p> MIAN: So by 1950, the S&amp;P 500 was stuck at the 20 level on the index for about 13, 14 years. And in the 1950s when you finally broke out. And between 1950 to 1968, which is the first secular bull period, you had a gain of about 450%. You had 1950s, which is the best decade for stocks ever, we forget. But that still, that whole period actually had three recessions. It had the Korean War, it had the Cuban Missile Crisis, it had the race riots, it had three corrections of over 20%. It had bond yields that went from 2.2% to nearly 6% and yet equities did well. That was a period of 1950 to 1968.</p><p> The second, and what&#39;s interesting about that period, is the fact that valuations actually peaked in 1961. Yet the market peaked in 1968.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So in other words, despite falling multiples, the prices continue to go higher.</p><p> MIAN: Yeah, so —</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Interesting.</p><p> MIAN: Valuations are ebb and flow. So the peak in valuation was in 1961, at 22 times multiple, but by 1968, even when the index made it stop, the PE was trading at 18 times. And the reason that&#39;s important is because there&#39;s a lot of talk about valuation now. And I feel like we may have seen the valuations peak for this cycle in 2021 at a 23 times forward PE. But that doesn&#39;t mean necessarily the secular bear market is over. So this secular bear market that we&#39;re in today began in 2013 when we finally broke above the 1,500 level that was capping the index since 2000.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right, so it was a 13 year secular bear market that had huge rallies, huge sell-offs, but you never got above that 2000 peak.</p><p> MIAN: And the second bull market began with a 4p of 13. We rose to 23. Last October we bottomed around 15 in a bit. And we&#39;re at 18 now. So again, this is 13 to 23, down to 15. We will not get to 23 in my opinion, but can we get to 20, 21? Sure, I think so.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So you mentioned the Korean War, you mentioned recessions. wrote about the JFK assassination, the Cuban Missile Crisis, a lot of things happen. How do we contextualize an extraneous event like the pandemic? Does it say to us, “Hey, this secular bull market is over” or does it just cause a wobble and we go back to the prior trend?</p><p> MIAN: So every secular bull market usually has like this mid-cycle crash.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right, &#39;73, &#39;74.</p><p> MIAN: Was a bear market actually.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Was in the middle of the bear market. You&#39;re saying bull markets have a secular market.</p><p> MIAN: Even a secular bull market has like a mid-cycle crash right so for example in the 1950 to 1968 bull market, the mid-cycle crash was the 1961 Kennedy bear market, the market fell down 30%. In the 1980 to 2000 market you had the mid-cycle crash and the 1987 crash.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: You had 1987, you had 1997, you had 1998 there were a number of really substantial.</p><p> MIAN: But do you have an event that really shocks investors right just like 1987 was very shocking and the decline in in the Kennedy bear market was very shocking, happened very quickly. And the pandemic was something like that. It was a mid-cycle crash in the way I perceive it. And so what&#39;s more important, I think, apart from just the technical conversation we were having around the indices and the breakouts, the pandemic made a significant difference from a fundamental standpoint. Because obviously fundamental underpinning to the secular bull market, you know, number one is the fact that households are in better financial conditions than they have been since, you know, the GFC.</p><p> But number two is from a demographic standpoint.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> MIAN: The millennials are now the largest generation in America. And if you think about the 1980 secular bull market, 1981 is when you had the baby boomers begin to turn 35, entering their peak earning years. The millennials started doing that in 2016. And the pandemic was important because after the pandemic, household wealth for millennials increased.</p><p> So if you compare it in present dollars, So when the boomer turned 35 in 1981, his net worth was around $136,000. In comparable dollars today, the millennials at $128,000.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So comparable on an inflation-adjusted basis.</p><p> MIAN: Absolutely. And what&#39;s more interesting is that the pandemic, I think, created this psychological fear and anxiety about wanting financial safety and securing your financial future. So you&#39;ve seen more home ownership interest and more stock participation because the pandemic was like this visceral death experience.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Wake up call.</p><p> MIAN: Wakeup call and you want to — and money&#39;s a proxy for safety. So you&#39;ve seen this dynamic where millennials are increasingly taking participation in financial markets and home ownership. And like so home ownership has increased from 38% to 46% for millennials over the last seven years. And that&#39;s going to continue to increase. So they&#39;re entering the peak earning years and that I think that&#39;s demographic impulse are still underappreciated.</p><p> RI